    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7019c30506ef5d7b",
      "text": "'Convivial Tools' are tools, technologies & infrastructures for enacting the commons in open, enlivening ways. They foster relations within and beyond the human world and bring about small, slow and beautifully simple energy-efficient solutions. They are accessible to everybody and easy to use. They invite for creative adaptation to one's own context.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "4474882e30bf4a99",
      "text": "Our use of the concept is inspired by the Croatian-Austrian philosopher Ivan Illich ([https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Illich wiki]). In 1973 he published 'Tools for [[Conviviality]]', with a strong focus on spotting the thresholds where [industrial]\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "e8c17e36713b1d57",
      "text": "<blockquote>\n \"productivity backfires into counter-productivity.\" (Vetter 2016:4)\n</blockquote>"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9f97aa6c2fce05f0",
      "text": "We use Illich's term but refer to a framework developed by Andrea Vetter in her PhD research between 2011 and 2017. Vetter speaks about \"convivial technologies,\" a term Illich did not use."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9acce2f0677490f8",
      "text": "For Ivan Illich the word 'tool' ..."
