      "text": "The idea of [[interdependence]] is central to both: \n- interdependence between human beings\n- interdependence between human beings and technology "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "d7adc1e9fdf2b344",
      "text": "We conclude from the \"conviviality literature\" inspired by Illich that there is a need for creativity and autonomy *for and through* the use of convivial tools & technologies. Using convivial tools helps making a given [[commons]] structurally independent from proprietarian \"closed\" tools and contributes to [[commoning]] as a [[creatively adaptive]] process."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "30037f0e2cdf8032",
      "text": "# The Five Core Dimensions of Convivial Tools"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "603b1c0cb2d5cff3",
      "text": "Below, the five dimensions of convivial tools are named, explained and illustrated by examples. The complete framework assesses each dimension based on the level of material, production, uses or [[infrastructure]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "05efb208145d7e91",
      "text": "<blockquote>\n\n\"be part of an ecological cycle and to be able to directly see this relatedness on their own ground, in their own garden.\"</blockquote>\n\nThe central question for the dimension of relatedness is then: what does it bring about between people?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "be145a9bbb811b7c",
      "text": "- [[Relatedness]]\nConvivialists assume that human beings are not just capable of relating to others, but dependent on relationships to others. Tools, technologies and [[infrastructures]] are crucial for enacting and maintaining these relations. Therefore, developing and using convivial technology implies the activation and expansion of human relationships and capacities.\n-> For example, building composting toilet systems or kitchen waste bokashi are convivial technologies because they are driven by the desire to"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8c6df0c437423c28",
      "text": "- [[Accessibility]] \nDo people have access to the design and knowledge needed to create convivial technologies?  This could be a matter of open source licenses, adequate documentation and standards, and cultural barriers (such as gender norms or discrimination).  \nOwnership of a technology can matter as well in terms of long-term control, access and use. Vetter: \"The central question is: who can build or use it where and how?\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4c2efc10aaec0f25",
      "text": "- [[Adaptability]] \nRefers to the independence from state-owned infrastructures allowing for the use of everyday tools  in order to follow own purposes, train skills and empower people. It also refers to the need to be able to decide whether one wants to be independet or linked. \nThe central question is therefor: How independent and linkable is a tool?\nThe slogan would be: Use small, slow and energy-efficient solutions!\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "20390c4d9e56a5d0",
      "text": "\nAn example is [[Open Source Ecology]] in [[Germany]] which cares for several aspects of adaptability on a technological level, most importantly [[modularity], [[scalability]] and [[suitability for D.I.Y]] (see OSEG, 2015)\n\nAccording to Andrea Vetter, the \n<blockquote>\nsmallest possible scale can also be rather big, as in the use of currently over 200 composting toilets for the 70.000 guests of the annual 5-day Fusion Festival, which makes clear that the composting of a big amount of stuff coming in a very short time requires different measures than the usual composting toilet used all year round by a more or less constant amount of family members.“ \n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "130c191f0420c00b",
      "text": "- [[Bio-interaction]]\nRefers to the idea to not only be less harmful to the environment, but to be useful in an ecological cycle. Examples are [[Permaculture]] or Terra Preta do Indío, a very fertile human made soil, produced since about 1000 years by the indigenous population in the Amazonian region.  \nBio-interaction is a [[Care-Honouring]] notion aiming at co-productivity. \nThe central question is: How does it interact with living organisms?\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "e3471c9b54a6bd05",
      "text": "<blockquote>\n\n[[Care]] in this sense means to contribute beneficially to ecosystems, not only to “produce no waste”, but also to “obtain a yield” (David Holmgren, 2013)\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "fcb629741fdcfc0d",
      "text": "Andrea Vetter points to the emerging community of bio-hackers, (see [[bio-hacking]]) who want to produce [[Open Source]] materials that are useful and degradable, but this movement is still in its very beginnings and its basic ethics to open source DNA as “code of life” could also lead to hazardous developments (Meyer, 2012)\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2b1a9cd8cdb003a1",
      "text": "- [[Appropriateness]]\nA convivial technology must take account of the entire context, local circumstances (are suitable materials and skills available?) Efficiency and tim-saving features must be balanced against the need for time for socially enlivening activity (\"Allow joyful time\").  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "30740162c99ddb9e",
      "text": "# Realms of Implementation"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fb893456ffa18a96",
      "text": "- [[CONSTITUTING TOOLS]]: foundational structures of state power vs foundational structures of commoning\n- Tools for [[KNOWLEDGE CREATION]]:\n- [[SOCIALIZING TOOLS]]: national vs commons narratives, rituals, ethics, norms\n- [[INFRASTRUCTURES]]: \"natural monopolies\" vs. collaborative infrastructures\n- [[FINANCE]]: State Treasury vs collaborative finance\n- Legal Tools or simply [[LAW]]: State Laws vs Vernacular Law\n\n"
    },
